2026-04-21 01:40:37 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module relay contacts', 'ambient sensor module relay drive / coil circuit', 'ambient sensor module switched-cables indicator LED path'] hypothesis_explanation='All voltage measurements (battery, PSU output, control-module output, and load input) remain essentially steady at ~11.8–12 V, including during the apparent 0.5 s lamp "off" event. Continuity of both lamps and the load-module wiring is normal, and the PSU LED is steady. The relay has been observed mechanically in the closed state and the 20 s behavior persists independent of adjustments to the timing potentiometer, yet the circuit simulator recurrently reports a non‑converging/oscillating state centered in the control module’s switched path.\n\nGiven that the ambient-sensor timing and comparator circuits (including the timing potentiometer) have already been replaced or verified good, the remaining plausible fault that could intermittently interrupt current or create an apparent oscillatory state while leaving DC levels nearly unchanged is a defect in the relay switching path itself: pitted/oxidized contacts, marginal contact pressure, or a parasitic/leakage path through the indicator LED circuitry tied to the switched cables. Such a defect can cause microsecond–millisecond scale interruptions or nonlinear conduction every ~20 s as the coil or contact geometry crosses a threshold, which would be perceived as a brief blink while still reading near-normal average DC voltages.\n\nTherefore, I hypothesize that the ambient sensor module’s relay assembly (contacts and associated drive/indicator circuitry) is faulty. Replacing/repairing the relay contacts and their drive path should eliminate the periodic 20‑second lamp dropout and the associated simulated instability.'
