2026-04-21 01:41:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module internal wiring between battery negative terminal and external negative output cable / LED reference node'] hypothesis_explanation='All active functional components in the ambient sensor and load modules, as well as their interconnecting cables, lamps, diode, relay, timing and sensitivity circuits, have been effectively ruled out by prior replacement attempts and tests. The battery voltage is stable at 12 V, and the PSU output measures ~11.87 V with the PSU LED on continuously, confirming a solid positive path. The symptom is a brief complete loss of lamp current about every 20 s, but measurements at the control output and load input remain essentially steady, and the relay stays closed; simulations repeatedly report an unstable/oscillating state.\n\nThis combination strongly suggests that the problem is not an intentional control action but an intermittent reference/return path issue common to the entire system. Because the negative side of the battery, the PSU LED reference, and the negative output cable share the same internal node or trace inside the power supply module, an intermittent connection or marginal solder joint on that internal negative node would occasionally open or significantly increase its impedance. When that occurs, the whole series string (sensor module, load module, lamps) momentarily loses a solid return path, so lamp current drops to near zero and the lamp appears to turn off for ~0.5 s. The positive voltages measured with respect to an external ground can remain apparently normal, especially in simulation, even while the return node is intermittently floating or oscillating, which explains the non‑converging / unstable state reports.\n\nThus the most consistent single root cause is a faulty or intermittent internal connection on the power supply module’s negative return path: specifically, the wiring/trace or solder joint between the battery negative terminal and the external negative output cable (and associated LED reference node) inside the power supply module. Repairing or reworking that internal negative connection should eliminate the periodic brief lamp shutdowns.'
