2026-04-21 01:41:47 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module internal supply decoupling / stability network (bypass capacitor across its supply rails)'] hypothesis_explanation='All module outputs, cables, lamps, relay, comparator/timing network, sensor, and PSU wiring have been ruled out by replacement with no change in symptoms. The supply voltage from the battery and at the module outputs is essentially steady during the 20‑s cycle, and both main and indicator lamps stay lit except for the brief, strictly periodic 0.5‑s outage, while the relay is observed to remain closed. The simulator repeatedly reports a non‑converging, unstable/oscillating state at nodes associated with the control electronics, not at the lamps or relay contacts.\n\nThis combination—stable external 12 V, correct behavior of sensing/relay elements when replaced, yet persistent, low‑frequency periodic disturbance and simulation ‘oscillation’ internal to the control circuitry—strongly indicates an internal supply‑stability problem local to the ambient sensor module’s electronics rather than a functional fault in timing or switching elements themselves. The only remaining untested component that could periodically upset the internal operation without dropping the measured module output is the local decoupling / bypass capacitor (or associated stability network) across the control IC’s Vcc‑GND rails.\n\nIf this capacitor is open, intermittent, or of grossly wrong value, the internal control circuit can enter a relaxation‑type oscillation or marginally stable state every ~20 s as charge/discharge or leakage effects build up, momentarily disturbing the drive to the relay and hence the lamp, even though the main 12 V rails appear steady at the external terminals. Therefore the most plausible remaining root cause is a faulty or missing ambient sensor module internal supply decoupling / stability network (bypass capacitor).'
