2026-04-21 01:41:58 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module internal series resistance / current‑limiting path between battery and output (including battery internal resistance, wiring, or unintended resistive element)'] hypothesis_explanation='All control‑module and load‑module elements have effectively been ruled out by prior correct repair attempts: relay, timing/sensitivity circuits, internal supply decoupling, indicator paths, series diode, lamps and their wiring, and all inter‑module cabling (including polarity mistakes) are confirmed not faulty. Measurements show: (1) the battery is a stiff 12.0 V at its terminals over the entire cycle; (2) the PSU output is about 11.87 V; (3) the control‑module output and the load input are ~11.84–11.85 V; (4) the lamp itself sees about 11.0 V, with no reported collapse of the upstream supply during the 0.5 s events. The lamp clearly turns fully off briefly every ~20 s, but the control relay is observed to remain closed and its output voltage does not drop, and the lamp/diode path components are good. The only remaining plausible mechanism is that the effective source impedance feeding the entire chain occasionally increases (or the series drop increases) enough that the lamp current momentarily falls to nearly zero, yet the measured node voltages (taken with a high‑impedance instrument) remain close to nominal.\n\nA small but abnormal series resistance or intermittent resistive path between the battery and the PSU output – such as a partially damaged trace, corroded or loose battery contact, or an unintended series resistor in the PSU module – can cause the lamp to sit in a marginal, unstable operating point where small internal oscillations (reported by the simulator as a non‑converging state) drive the current to zero every ~20 s for ~0.5 s, while high‑impedance voltage readings appear nearly steady. Because every downstream component has been exonerated by failed repair attempts, the root cause is best attributed to a fault local to the power‑supply module’s internal series path from the battery to its output (including the battery’s own internal resistance and immediate connections), which was not explicitly replaced or repaired in earlier hypotheses.'
