2026-04-21 01:42:08 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module 12 V lithium battery'] hypothesis_explanation='All module circuits, wiring, lamps, diodes, relay path, timing/sensitivity electronics, indicators, polarity and inter‑module cabling have been tested or replaced with no effect, and supply/output voltages remain nominal and steady from battery terminals through the control output and at the load input.\n\nThe only remaining element that can produce a strictly time‑periodic (~20 s) complete loss of lamp current for ~0.5 s, with otherwise normal voltage readings and no true open circuit in any module, is an internal protective/management function of the 12 V lithium battery itself (e.g., a built‑in protection/BMS board resetting or performing brief periodic balancing/diagnostics, momentarily interrupting current despite the terminal voltage staying near 12 V under the meter’s light load).\n\nBecause all external circuitry has been ruled out as faulty via prior unsuccessful repair attempts, the root cause is best explained by the battery assembly: the 12 V lithium battery (including its internal protection electronics) is intermittently cutting off load current for about 0.5 s every ~20 s while maintaining near‑nominal open‑circuit voltage, thereby causing the observed regular lamp turn‑off with no accompanying changes in module voltages detectable by the previous tests.'
