2026-04-21 01:42:24 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module green LED indicator circuit (LED plus its series resistor and wiring)'] hypothesis_explanation='All supply, control, and load components and their interconnections have been tested or hypothetically replaced with no effect, yet the system continues to show a brief 0.5 s brightness drop every ~20 s while all measured DC voltages at the PSU output and control output remain essentially steady and the relay and indicator lamps show no corresponding activity. The only remaining active element drawing current from the same 12 V source that has not yet been considered as a fault is the power supply module’s own green indicator LED (and its series resistor/wiring), which is wired permanently across the battery in parallel with the rest of the system.\n\nIf this LED indicator circuit is intermittently going into a high‑current or partial‑short condition (for example due to an internal LED defect, breakdown in the LED package, or a damaged series resistor or its solder joints intermittently shorting), it can momentarily steal a substantial amount of current from the battery every ~20 s. That would create a transient load step and an internal oscillatory or non‑convergent condition in the simulator, causing the main lamp’s brightness to dip very briefly without a large, easily measured drop in the external 12 V node voltages. The relay remains closed and the control/indicator lamps stay lit, consistent with the observations; only the main load, being the largest current consumer, exhibits the visible dip.\n\nTherefore I hypothesize that the fault lies in the power supply module green LED indicator circuit (LED plus its series resistor/wiring) intermittently drawing excessive current or partially shorting, leading to the observed periodic 0.5 s lamp dimming without obvious voltage collapse at the measurement points.'
