2026-04-21 01:43:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control‑module to load‑module fast‑connection terminals pair that is currently unused (the second cable pair at the control module)', 'wiring configuration between the two cable pairs on the ambient sensor module (mis‑mating / partial short between the switched pair and the unswitched pair)'] hypothesis_explanation='Given all prior component‑level hypotheses have been disproven and every active element (battery, PSU LED path, sensor/comparator, relay, indicator LED, series diode, both lamps, and all presently‑used connector pairs) has tested good, the only remaining plausible cause for a periodic 0.5 s extinguishing of only the main lamp, with supply voltage stable and relay definitely closed, is a configuration fault involving the *second* (nominally unused) cable pair on the ambient sensor module.\n\nIf that spare pair (or its fast‑connection terminals) has been inadvertently cross‑coupled or partially shorted into the switched output pair going to the load module—for example, by mis‑mating the fast connectors so that one conductor from the switched pair is tied into a conductor from the unused pair—then the control module output to the load can be momentarily disturbed at a low duty‑cycle when internal circuitry on the unused pair slews or re‑biases. In the physical device this would manifest as a very brief full turn‑off of the main lamp every ~20 s, while all monitored supply rails and the relay contact itself appear normal, and while the internal indicator lamp (in parallel with the main lamp) remains effectively unaffected in observable brightness.\n\nAll straightforward faults within the three modules and along the currently‑used cable pair have been ruled out by explicit repair attempts. The only remaining realistic root cause consistent with all observations and with the modular cabling description is an incorrect or unintended interconnection involving the otherwise unused second cable pair on the ambient sensor (control) module and its mating fast‑connection terminals to the load module. Repairing or correcting that connector configuration (separating the pairs so only the proper switched pair feeds the load, with no cross‑coupling or partial short to the spare pair) should eliminate the periodic lamp outage.'
