2026-04-21 01:43:41 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module output cable pair and load module input cable pair (fast-connection terminals) currently in use, mated in a way that cross-connects + and − between the two modules'] hypothesis_explanation='All individual components (battery, PSU, sensor electronics, relay, indicator LEDs, lamps, diode, and internal wirings) have been ruled out by prior correct-repair attempts. Voltage at PSU output and at the control-output pair is stable; the relay stays closed and indicators are steady, so the ambient sensor module is continuously delivering a solid 12 V. The load module lamps and wiring are nominal, yet the main lamp briefly turns fully off every ~20 s with the internal indicator lamp remaining on and supply voltages not collapsing.\n\nThe only remaining plausible mechanism is a configuration/connection fault involving the detachable fast-connection terminals between the ambient sensor module and the load module. If the two conductors of the output pair are cross-mated such that the load’s “+” lead is connected to the control’s − wire and the load’s “−” lead to the control’s + wire (or more subtly, if one side of the pair is flipped relative to the other), the series diode and lamp network can see a periodically opposing or near-zero effective voltage as the simulator iterates, leading to the observed half‑second extinguish of the main lamp while the internal indicator, in parallel and with different characteristics, can remain lit. This is consistent with the repeated reports of simulation non‑convergence/oscillation while measured DC values look almost normal on simple probes.\n\nSince every internal module fault has been excluded, a mis‑mated polarity (crossed +/−) at the fast‑connection terminals between the ambient sensor module output and the load module input is the most likely remaining root cause, producing a subtle, configuration‑dependent intermittent behavior rather than a permanent open or short in any one component.'
